Below is an example of how you might modify a CSS codebase to meet the requirements using SASS syntax. Please note that without the original CSS, I can only provide a generic example. The code includes comments to explain how each requirement is addressed.

```scss
// Define color variables for light and dark mode
:root {
  --primary-color: #007bff;
  --background-color: #ffffff;
  --text-color: #000000;

  // Dark mode colors
  [data-theme='dark'] {
    --primary-color: #0d6efd;
    --background-color: #343a40;
    --text-color: #ffffff;
  }
}

// Mixin for responsive design
@mixin respond-to($breakpoint) {
  @if $breakpoint == 'phone' {
    @media (max-width: 600px) { @content; }
  } @else if $breakpoint == 'tablet' {
    @media (max-width: 900px) { @content; }
  } @else if $breakpoint == 'desktop' {
    @media (min-width: 901px) { @content; }
  }
}

// Mixin for cross-browser compatible keyframes animation
@mixin keyframes($name) {
  @-webkit-keyframes #{$name} { @content; }
  @-moz-keyframes #{$name} { @content; }
  @-o-keyframes #{$name} { @content; }
  @keyframes #{$name} { @content; }
}

// Base styles
body {
  background-color: var(--background-color);
  color: var(--text-color);
  font-family: 'Arial', sans-serif;

  // Responsive design
  @include respond-to('phone') {
    font-size: 14px;
  }

  @include respond-to('tablet') {
    font-size: 16px;
  }

  @include respond-to('desktop') {
    font-size: 18px;
  }
}

// Button styles with animation
button {
  background-color: var(--primary-color);
  color: var(--text-color);
  border: none;
  padding: 10px 20px;
  cursor: pointer;
  transition: background-color 0.3s ease;

  &:hover {
    background-color: darken(var(--primary-color), 10%);
  }

  // Animation for user engagement
  &:focus {
    @include keyframes(buttonPulse) {
      0% { transform: scale(1); }
      50% { transform: scale(1.1); }
      100% { transform: scale(1); }
    }
    animation: buttonPulse 1s infinite;
  }
}

// Link styles with animation
a {
  color: var(--primary-color);
  text-decoration: none;
  transition: color 0.3s ease;

  &:hover {
    color: darken(var(--primary-color), 20%);
    text-decoration: underline;

    // Animation for user engagement
    @include keyframes(linkPulse) {
      0% { transform: translateY(0); }
      50% { transform: translateY(-5px); }
      100% { transform: translateY(0); }
    }
    animation: linkPulse 0.5s ease-in-out;
  }
}

// Dark mode toggle button
.dark-mode-toggle {
  position: fixed;
  top: 10px;
  right: 10px;
  background-color: var(--background-color);
  color: var(--text-color);
  border: 1px solid var(--primary-color);
  padding: 5px 10px;
  cursor: pointer;

  &:hover {
    background-color: var(--primary-color);
    color: var(--background-color);
  }
}
```

Explanation:

1. **SASS Syntax**: The code uses SASS variables, mixins, and nested syntax.
2. **Dark Mode Toggle**: CSS custom properties (variables) are used to define color schemes for light and dark modes. A `data-theme` attribute selector is used to switch colors for dark mode.
3. **Responsive Design**: A mixin named `respond-to` is created to handle media queries for different breakpoints (phone, tablet, desktop).
4. **CSS Animations**: Keyframes are defined using a mixin for cross-browser compatibility. Animations are applied to buttons and links to improve user engagement.
5. **Cross-Browser Compatibility**: Vendor prefixes are included in the keyframes mixin to ensure animations work across different browsers.
6. **Performance Optimization**: By using variables and mixins, redundant code is reduced. Also, the use of `@content` inside mixins allows for writing media queries and animations only once, and then including them as needed, which keeps the code DRY (Don't Repeat Yourself).

To implement the dark mode toggle feature, you would need to add a small JavaScript snippet to toggle the `data-theme` attribute on the root element:

```javascript
const toggleButton = document.querySelector('.dark-mode-toggle');
toggleButton.addEventListener('click', () => {
  const theme = document.documentElement.getAttribute('data-theme') === 'dark' ? 'light' : 'dark';
  document.documentElement.setAttribute('data-theme', theme);
});
```

This JavaScript code listens for clicks on the `.dark-mode-toggle` button and toggles the `data-theme` attribute between 'light' and 'dark', which in turn switches the color scheme based on the CSS variables defined for each theme.
